<h2 id="basic-structure-">Basic Structure <a id="struct"></a></h2>
<p>The basic form of <code class="highlighter-rouge">find</code> command looks like the below.</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>find <span class="o">[</span><span class="nt">-H</span><span class="o">]</span> <span class="o">[</span><span class="nt">-L</span><span class="o">]</span> <span class="o">[</span><span class="nt">-P</span><span class="o">]</span> <span class="o">[</span><span class="nt">-D</span> debugopt] <span class="o">[</span><span class="nt">-Olevel</span><span class="o">]</span> <span class="o">[</span>path] <span class="o">[</span><span class="nb">expr</span><span class="o">]</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>There are lot of options but donâ€™t be scared. Just think of it as this way:</p>

<p><code class="highlighter-rouge">-H</code>, <code class="highlighter-rouge">-L</code>, <code class="highlighter-rouge">-P</code> â†’ How should I treat symbolic links?</p>

<p><code class="highlighter-rouge">-D</code> â†’ Should I print debug messages (that you specfically asked for)?</p>

<p><code class="highlighter-rouge">-O</code> â†’ How should I optimize it?</p>

<p><code class="highlighter-rouge">path</code> â†’ Where should I begin?</p>

<p><code class="highlighter-rouge">expr</code> â†’ What should I find?</p>

<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="treatement-of-symbolic-links-">Treatement of Symbolic Links <a id="treatment"></a></h3>

<p>The frist three options(<code class="highlighter-rouge">-H</code>, <code class="highlighter-rouge">-L</code>, <code class="highlighter-rouge">-P</code>) are related to treatments of symbolic links. <br />
Letâ€™s take a look at each treatment option.</p>

<p>For the purpose explanation, I created a such directory hierarchy:</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>test/
â”œâ”€â”€ blog.c
â”œâ”€â”€ hello.c
â”œâ”€â”€ my-blog -&gt; /home/myoi/Documents/blog
</code></pre></div></div>

<p><code class="highlighter-rouge">my-blog</code> is indeed a symbolic link which points to <code class="highlighter-rouge">/home/myoi/Documents/blog</code>, and the hierarchy
of this directory looks like the below:</p>
<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>blog
â””â”€â”€ file1.c
â””â”€â”€ file2.c
â””â”€â”€ post
    â”œâ”€â”€ post1.md
    â””â”€â”€ post2.md
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>To find a file in a directory, we can use <code class="highlighter-rouge">-type f</code> option. <br />
Letâ€™s use this option and try to find all files starting at <code class="highlighter-rouge">test</code> directory.</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>$ find test/ -type f

test/hello.c
test/blog.c
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>As a result, we got <code class="highlighter-rouge">hello.c</code> and <code class="highlighter-rouge">blog.c</code>. Is this what we intended? <br />
From the structure of the directory we saw earlier above, we know there exist more than 2 files.</p>

<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="-p-option-">-P Option <a id="popt"></a></h3>
<p>Letâ€™s attach <code class="highlighter-rouge">-P</code> option and try that again.</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>$ find -P test/ -type f

test/hello.c
test/blog.c
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>The result is same.</p>

<p>When we donâ€™t specify any options for symbolic link treatments, the command follows the default
behavior which is <code class="highlighter-rouge">-P</code> and <strong>-P never follows the symbolic link</strong>.</p>

<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="-l-option-">-L Option <a id="lopt"></a></h3>
<p>Letâ€™s take a look at the case of <strong>-L</strong>.</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>$ find -L test/ -type f

test/hello.c
test/my-blog/file1.c
test/my-blog/file2.c
test/my-blog/post/post2.md
test/my-blog/post/post1.md
test/blog.c
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>All files are printed as we expected. <br />
From this result, we can learn that <strong>-L follows symbolic link</strong> when seen.</p>

<p><br /></p>
<h3 id="-h-option-">-H Option <a id="hopt"></a></h3>
<p>Now letâ€™s take a look at the last case which is <strong>-H</strong>.</p>

<p>At first glance, the behavior of this option seems similar to -P.</p>

<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>$ find -H test/ -type f

test/hello.c
test/blog.c
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Now look at this example:</p>
<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>$ find -H test/my-blog/ -type f

test/my-blog/file1.c
test/my-blog/file2.c
test/my-blog/post/post2.md
test/my-blog/post/post1.md
test/blog.c
</code></pre></div></div>

<p><strong>-H follows symbolic link ONLY when the given path (argument) is a symbolic link</strong>.
The first exampleâ€™s argument was not a symbolic link so it behaves like -P. But in the
second example, the argument is symbolic link so now it acts like -L and follows the link.</p>

<p><br /></p>
<h2 id="tldr-">TL;DR <a id="tldr"></a></h2>
<div class="highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>$ find -[P/L/H] test/ -type f
</code></pre></div></div>

<ul>
  <li><strong>-P</strong>: never follows symbolic link</li>
  <li><strong>-L</strong>: follows symbolic link</li>
  <li><strong>-H</strong>: follows symbolic link only if given argument is symbolic link</li>
</ul>

<p><br /></p>
